# hrtf_course

Cue editing and behavioural analysis for the practical psychoacoustics
course.  Used to:

* design **cue-frequency-shift** conditions (manipulate a recorded
  HRTF in a chosen band, write a new SOFA), and
* analyse **localization-test results** that come back from the rig
  as ``Subject`` pickles, grouped by condition.

HRTF recording and the localization tests themselves run on the rig
machine via [`hrtf_relearning`](https://github.com/pfriedrich-hub/hrtf_relearning)
— this repo only covers the laptop-side cue editing and post-hoc
analysis.

## Install

The project ships with a populated `.venv/` containing all dependencies.

1. Open the `hrtf_course/` folder in PyCharm.
2. PyCharm auto-detects `.venv/` as the project interpreter (if it
   doesn't, point it at `hrtf_course/.venv/bin/python` via
   Settings → Project → Python Interpreter → Add → Existing).
3. Open a script in `scripts/` and run the `# %%` cells.

If `.venv/` is missing or broken (fresh clone, deleted, etc.),
re-create it with [`uv`](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/):

```bash
cd ~/projects/hrtf_course
uv sync
```

## Workflow

```
                cue editing                    localization tests
   ┌──────────────────────────────┐        ┌─────────────────────┐
   │   hrtf_course (this repo)    │  SOFA  │    rig machine      │
   │  scripts/01_design_*.py      │ ────► │   hrtf_relearning   │
   │                              │        │                     │
   │  scripts/02_analyze.py       │ ◄──── │                     │
   └──────────────────────────────┘  pkl   └─────────────────────┘
```

### Data layout

This repo is the single source of truth for data on the laptop side.
Subject pickles and SOFAs live under ``data/``:

```
hrtf_course/
└── data/
    ├── sofa/           # {subject}.sofa  (recorded) + manipulated SOFAs
    └── results/        # {subject}.pkl   (Subject pickle from rig runs)
```

Copy files in/out of those folders to move data between this repo and
the rig:

```bash
# Bring a recording over from the rig before designing conditions
cp /path/to/rig/data/hrtf/sofa/AGV.sofa  ~/projects/hrtf_course/data/sofa/

# After running localization tests at the rig, bring the pickle back
cp /path/to/rig/data/results/AGV.pkl    ~/projects/hrtf_course/data/results/

# And take a manipulated SOFA you designed here back to the rig
cp ~/projects/hrtf_course/data/sofa/AGV_shift_+10pct.sofa  /path/to/rig/data/hrtf/sofa/
```

You can override the locations entirely with the env vars
``HRTF_COURSE_SOFA_DIR`` and ``HRTF_COURSE_RESULTS_DIR``.

## What the package gives you

```python
from hrtf_course import (
    # Cue editing
    shift_band,            # cepstral split: warp ONLY the high-quefrency
                           #   detail inside [low, high]; broad envelope
                           #   (externalisation) is preserved
    octave_band,           # octave_band(8000) -> (5657, 11314) Hz
    Condition,             # name + base subject + manipulation function

    # Preview
    preview,               # spectrogram + VSI dissimilarity, no I/O

    # Analysis (post-rig)
    list_runs,             # peek at all runs in a Subject pickle
    collect_results,       # pool runs into a tidy DataFrame
    plot_compare,          # metric per condition, one dot per run
    plot_tolerance_curve,  # metric vs. VSI dissimilarity
)
```

## Minimal example — design + preview a condition

Assumes ``data/sofa/AGV.sofa`` is in place (copy it in from the rig
first):

```python
from hrtf_course import Condition, shift_band, octave_band, preview

low, high = octave_band(8000)

cond = Condition(
    name="shift_+10pct",
    base_subject="AGV",
    fn=lambda h: shift_band(h, low, high, factor=1.10),
)

preview.show(cond)            # original vs. manipulated, with VSI
sofa_name = cond.build_sofa() # writes data/sofa/AGV_shift_+10pct.sofa
print(sofa_name)
```

The full design script lives at ``scripts/01_design_conditions.py`` —
it builds a few shift conditions in one go and writes them all out.

## Minimal example — analyse a Subject pickle

After the rig sends back ``data/results/AGV.pkl``:

```python
from hrtf_course import list_runs, collect_results, plot_compare, plot_tolerance_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# 1. See what's in the pickle
print(list_runs("AGV"))

# 2. Pool the runs you care about (multiple runs per condition is fine)
df = collect_results(
    ["AGV"],
    condition_names=["recorded", "shift_-10pct", "shift_+10pct", "shift_+20pct"],
)
print(df[["subject", "condition", "run", "ele_rmse", "vsi_diss"]])

# 3. Plot
plot_compare(df, metric="ele_rmse", group="condition")
plot_tolerance_curve(df, x="vsi_diss", y="ele_rmse")
plt.show()
```

If a condition was run multiple times, each run shows up as a separate
dot in the plots.  To restrict to specific runs (e.g. drop a partial
sequence), pass ``runs=[...]`` to ``collect_results``.

The full analysis script lives at ``scripts/02_analyze.py``.

## How conditions are recovered from rig data

When the rig runs a localization test, it stores the SOFA name on the
sequence (``sequence.hrir``).  By convention the SOFA name is
``{base_subject}_{condition}.sofa`` — e.g. ``AGV_shift_+10pct.sofa`` —
so ``collect_results`` parses the condition back out by stripping the
``{base_subject}_`` prefix.  Sequences whose SOFA is exactly
``{base_subject}.sofa`` are reported as condition ``"recorded"``.

Condition names therefore have to be filename-safe: only
``A–Z``, ``a–z``, ``0–9``, ``_``, ``+``, ``-``, and ``.`` are allowed.

## VSI dissimilarity

``collect_results`` automatically computes
[Trapeau & Schönwiesner (2016)](https://doi.org/10.1121/1.4960400)
VSI dissimilarity vs. each subject's baseline HRTF, in the 5.7–11.3 kHz
peak band — a single scalar per run that quantifies how much the
spectral cues changed.  ``plot_tolerance_curve`` plots a behavioural
metric against it — the headline figure for the seminar.
